5":"1300年–1335年","1350–1450":"1350年–1450年","1260–1300":"1260年–1300年","1265–Female":"1265年–殁","1335":"1335年","1300":"1300年","1299":"1299年","1265":"1265年","1286":"1286年","1450":"1450年","1340":"1340年","1274":"1274年","1350":"1350年","1260":"1260年","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"爱尔兰萊音斯特迪 本 米亞斯","Écosse":"英国苏格兰","Slane Meath Ireland":"爱尔兰庫迪 米亞斯斯藍","lifeSummary":"当Richard Fleming \"Flandrensis\"于1286年出生在爱尔兰萊音斯特迪 本 米亞斯时，他的父亲Baldwin de Flanders le Fleming, Lord of Slane  \"Flandrensis\"26岁，母亲Lady Maria Martyn Le Fleming22岁。他于1299年与Marie Maria Martyn在爱尔兰庫迪 米亞斯斯藍结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世在英国苏格兰。"},"hr":{"1286–":"1286.–preminuo","1286–Male":"1286.–preminuo","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300.–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300.","1265–Female":"1265–preminula","1335":"1335","1300":"1300.","1299":"1299.","1265":"1265","1286":"1286.","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Irska","Écosse":"Škotska, United Kingdom","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Irska"},"cs":{"1286–":"1286–Zesnulý","1286–Male":"1286–Zesnulý","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Zesnulá","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Irsko","Écosse":"Skotsko, United Kingdom","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Irsko"},"da":{"1286–":"1286–Afdød","1286–Male":"1286–Afdød","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Afdød","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Irland","Écosse":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Irland"},"nl":{"1286–":"1286–Overleden","1286–Male":"1286–Overleden","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Overleden","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ierland","Écosse":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"1286–":"1286–Deceased","1286–Male":"1286–Deceased","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ireland","Écosse":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Fleming \"Flandrensis\" was born in 1286, in Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ireland, his father, Baldwin de Flanders le Fleming, Lord of Slane  \"Flandrensis\", was 26 and his mother, Lady Maria Martyn Le Fleming, was 22. He married Marie Maria Martyn in 1299, in Slane, County Meath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1286–":"1286–Surnud","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Iirimaa","Écosse":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1286–":"1286–Kuollut","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"1260","Slane Castle, Leinster, Meath, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Irlanti","Écosse":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Slane Meath Ireland":"Slane, County Meath, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1286–":"1286–Décédé","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1260–1300":"1260–1300","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1260":"126